            "@type": "dctypes:Text",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><em><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">HT.II.L7</span></em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Carry on Tom<br /><br /></span></strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">This directive to &ldquo;carry on&rdquo; a particular plot thread is one that appears throughout the Working Notes (sometimes as &ldquo;carry through&rdquo;). On the Note for<em> David Copperfield</em> No. XIII, for instance, Dickens writes: &ldquo;Carry on the thread of Uriah [Heep], carefully, and not obtrusively&rdquo; (see <em>DC.XIII.L2</em>), and it appears throughout the Working Notes for <em>Bleak House</em>: &ldquo;Rosa &amp; Watt? Yes. Slightly. Carry on&rdquo; (BH_WN_04); &ldquo;Mr. Tulkinghorn? Carry on.&rdquo; (BH_WN_07); &ldquo;Esther and Allan? Yes. Carry on gently.&rdquo; (BH_WN_16). Dickens begins to use this phrase and similar language in subsequent novels (see, for example, <em>LD.V.L2</em>, <em>LD.VII.R10</em>, and <em>LD.XIII.L9 </em>for examples in <em>Little Dorrit</em>). Although this sequence is the only time this kind of language appears in the Working Notes for <em>Hard Times</em>, it highlights the importance of Dickens&rsquo;s decision to plan and write the novel in the monthly number format: with these three directives, Dickens identifies three interlinked threads to develop over the space of four weekly installments that are here conceived (and partially planned) as one &lsquo;number.&rsquo;</span></p>",
            "format": "text/html"
        }
